The paper deals with predicting the next event in asynchronous event sequences, which is a common problem in machine learning and artificial intelligence. The paper proposes two new architectures that model the evolution of the distribution on the probability simplex with time-dependent logistic normal and Dirichlet distributions. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), and cryptography and security (cs.CR), as these sub-categories often deal with probabilistic models and prediction problems. Additionally, the paper also discusses anomaly detection, which is a topic that falls under the sub-category of social and information networks (cs.SI). Finally, the paper uses RNNs, which are commonly used in the sub-category of information theory (cs.IT).
